France and Turkmenistan also share the burden of a “strongly anti-choice” approach to the issue – but for entirely different reasons, said Higgins.

As well as being a very Catholic country with strong religious foundations, France is now home to an increasingly vocal anti-abortion movement.

But the biggest cautionary tale of a country that is strongly advising against abortion – and that has a horrific, but very much unintended, impact on maternal mortality rates as a result – is Turkmenistan.

“Many women, in particular in rural areas of Turkmenistan, will attempt to self-induced an abortion…and in attempting to take things into their own hands, are often unaware of how to do it how to do it safely,” explained Higgins.

“What they do adopt is to run to a well in the middle of the night in the dead of winter, publicly induce an abortion and wait before they’re able to retrieve the product of conception, which often bleeds out on the ground, and are unable to get it to a hospital in time.

“That, mixed with the lack of any accompanying funding or even education in the area, means that many women will die in childbirth before the age of 50 as a direct result,” she said.

Meanwhile, “abortion is one of the sacred topics of study” among medical students, said Becker.
